  <h1 class="text-teal-600 font-bold text-4xl">
    Pricing</h1>
  <p style="margin-top:2em; margin-bottom:1.5em">A blog (a truncation of "weblog") is a type of website, or part of a website, that consists of discrete, typically informal, diary-style text entries called posts. Posts are generally displayed in reverse chronological order, so the most recent content appears first.
  Key Characteristics
  Content Format: While primarily textual, blogs often incorporate digital images, videos (vlogs), audio (podcasts), and links to other web pages.
  Style and Tone: They typically use an informal, conversational tone, which helps in connecting with readers and building a community.
  Interactivity: Most blogs allow visitors to leave comments and interact with the authors and each other, acting as a form of social networking.
  Focus: Bloggers often focus on a specific niche or topic, ranging from personal diaries to professional subjects like technology, finance, or food, establishing themselves as an authority in that field.
  Ease of Use: The rise of blogs was due in part to web publishing tools that made it easy for non-technical users to publish content online without needing HTML knowledge.
  Purpose and Use
  Blogs are used by a wide variety of individuals and organizations for different purposes:
  Individuals use them to share personal experiences, opinions, and creative work, building a personal brand.
  Businesses and organizations use blogs as an effective content marketing tool to engage with customers, drive website traffic through search engine optimization (SEO), and showcase expertise.
  Journalists and experts use them to provide real-time commentary, breaking news, or in-depth analysis on current events.
  Platforms and Monetization
  There are many platforms available to create a blog, such as WordPress.com and Blogger.com, many of which offer free hosting options.
  Bloggers can monetize their content through various methods, including:
  Displaying ads, often via advertising networks like Google AdSense.
  Affiliate marketing, where they earn commissions for promoting products or services.
  Selling their own digital or physical products, online courses, or consulting services.
  Sponsored content collaborations with brands.
</p>
